ortened form of French   Lafontaine  , a variant of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Fontenot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Ulysse, Andrus, Alcide, Andre, Edouard, Lucien, Marise, Monique, Remy.","French: variant of <b>Fonteneau</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), a topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from any of several places mainly in the westcentral part of France so named. The surname <i>Fontenot</i> is very rare in France.","History: Jean-Louis Fonteneau/Fontenot from Montierneuf in Vienne, France, married Louise-Angélique Henry in Mobile, AL, in 1726."]},{"name":"Fontenelle","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from (La) Fontenelle, the name of several places in various parts of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fontenette","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from Fontenette, the name of several places mainly in the central part of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fountain","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from one or more of the places in France named Fontaine, Fonteyne, or Lafontaine (see   Fontaine  ).","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a spring or well, from Middle English <i>fontayne</i> (Old French <i>fontaine</i>) ‘spring, fountain’, sometimes with a plural <i>-s</i>, and synonymous with   Well  , of which <i>Fountain(es)</i> may sometimes have been a translation."]},{"name":"Font","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Luis, Miguel, Rafael, Eduardo, Raul, Eugenio, Pedro, Roberto, Aida.","Catalan and southern French: topographic name for someone living near a spring or well, Catalan and Occitan <i>font</i> ‘spring, well’ (from Latin <i>fons</i>, genitive <i>fontis</i>).","English: variant of   Fant  ."]},{"name":"Fontan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Angel, Benigno, Carlos, Jose, Juana, Manuel, Pedro, Adolfo, Aida, Alfredo, Candido, Emilia.","Spanish and Galician (<b>Fontán</b>): habitational name from any of the many places called Fontán, from <i>fontán</i> ‘spring’.","French: variant of   Fontaine  ."]}]},{"name":"Jehanne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian feminine form of   Johan ."],"variants":[{"name":"Joanne","meanings":["From Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, and so a doublet of   Joan .  This too was revived as a given name in its own right in the first half of the 20th century. It has to some extent been influenced by the independently formed combination <i>Jo Anne</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jehanne D'ORVILLE-DE FONTAINE was born in 1180, in Orville, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France, her father, ARNOULD I d'Orville, was 32 and her mother, Gilotte Somme, was 19. She had at least 1 daughter with Wauthier DE BAYENCOURT-DE BAUDIMONT. She died in 1239, in Bayencourt, Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1180–1239":"1180–1239","1165–1227":"1165–1227","1208–1249":"1208–1249","1148–1191":"1148–1191","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1239":"1239","1227":"1227","1249":"1249","1148":"1148","1165":"1165","1162":"1162","1182":"1182","1208":"1208","1180":"1180","1191":"1191","Bayencourt, Somme, Picardie, France":"Bayencourt, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Orville, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Orville, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1180–1239":"1180–1239","1165–1227":"1165–1227","1208–1249":"1208–1249","1148–1191":"1148–1191","1162–Female":"1162–Kuollut","1239":"1239","1227":"1227","1249":"1249","1148":"1148","1165":"1165","1162":"1162","1182":"1182","1208":"1208","1180":"1180","1191":"1191","Bayencourt, Somme, Picardie, France":"Ba